@richardkiss, I think I understand your https://github.com/richardkiss/pycoin/pull/94#issuecomment-87109930 better now after reading [this](https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=38903.msg476100#msg476100) (bitcointalk.org). Calling `ecdsa.possible_public_pairs_for_signature` might be the appropriate thing to do generally, but these tests' performance will suffer.

At the risk of introducing complexity, it's possible to implement two approaches:

* Where 2m < n, deduce the public keys from the signatures and then compare them (in order) to the public keys to find a sufficient number of matches;
* Where 2m >= n, walk through the signatures and public keys as [described in the Wiki](https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Script).

I have not looked into it in any detail, but perhaps there are some lower level routines we can borrow and experiment with from [vbuterin/pybitcointools](/vbuterin/pybitcointools)?

@santoshphilip It's actually a really good way for me to get more familiar with what's going on under the hood. Although I feel like I might be missing an easier way of doing things than what I have here for comparing near-equality of `IDF` objects. If you have a few minutes to review it that would be great.

```python
class IDF(object):
	... 
	
	def __almostequal__(self, other, places=7):
		for dtls1, dtls2 in zip(self.model.dtls, other.model.dtls):
			objlst1 = self.model.dt[dtls1]
			objlst2 = other.model.dt[dtls2]
			for obj1, obj2 in zip(objlst1, objlst2):
				for fld1, fld2 in zip(obj1, obj2):
					if not almostequal(fld1, fld2, places):
						return False
		return True

		
def almostequal(first, second, places=7):
	"""docstring for almostequal"""
	# convert to float first
	try:
		first = float(first)
		second = float(second)
	except ValueError:
		# handle non-float types
		return str(first) == str(second)
	# test floats for near-equality
	if round(abs(second-first), places) != 0:
		return False
	else:
		return True
```

