@khalibartan In python3 we can directly access the wrapped method. But am not sure about the performance difference in python 2. But shouldn't be much and ideally it should be just an extra check.

@yashu-seth No, it's not the same. What I meant is that the arguments for states in any method would either be just a state in the form of `(var, state)` (I don't think we are passing a single state anywhere but would be good to have) or a list of states in the form of `[(var1, state1), (var2, state2)]`, so we can simply handle the conversion based on whether we have a single state or a list of states. For example in the case of `reduce` your argument will be a list of states, similarly in the case of `query` method of inference algorithms you will be getting a list of states.

Also if we implement it in this way we won't need to change the decorator in future and it should work on any new method that we add.

