The lazy (and unreliable) way is to use the `BaseScheduler` and insert the agents into the scheduler in the order you want them to run in.

The better way will be to subclass the `BaseScheduler` and implement a step method that does what you need. For example:

```
class AgentTypeScheduler(BaseScheduler):
    def __init__(self, model, agent_class_order):
        super().__init__(model) # This syntax for python 3.
        self.class_order = class_order

    def _class_index(self, agent):
        # Returns a low number for classes you want to have come first
        if agent.__class__ in self.class_order:
            return self.class_order.index(agent.__class__)
       else:
           return len(self.class_order)

    def step(self):
        # sort the agent list by the class order, then call the BaseScheduler step
        self.agents = sorted(self.agents, key=self._class_index)
        super().step()
```

I wouldn't actually use that code since it is inefficient. It would be better to sort the agents only when new ones are added. You'd also have to do a little extra work to ensure that the original sort order remains the same on an add if that matters to you.

